  "final_answer": "## SpaceX Connectivity Segment — FY2025 YoY Growth Analysis\n\n### Source Figures (from SpaceX S-1, segment reporting — recast consolidated entity including xAI and X Holdings)\n\n| Metric ($ millions) | FY2025 | FY2024 | YoY $ Change | YoY Growth |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|---:|\n| Revenue | $11,387 | $7,599 | +$3,788 | **+49.85%** |\n| Income from Operations | $4,423 | $2,006 | +$2,417 | **+120.49%** |\n| Segment Adjusted EBITDA | $7,168 | $3,849 | +$3,319 | **+86.23%** |\n\nSegment Adjusted EBITDA is a non-GAAP measure defined in the S-1 as segment income (loss) from operations plus depreciation & amortization, share-based compensation, restructuring charges, and impairment. The Connectivity segment is primarily driven by Starlink (consumer subscribers plus enterprise/government aviation, maritime, mobility, and government business).\n\n### Margin Profile\n\n| Margin | FY2025 | FY2024 | Expansion |\n|---|---:|---:|---:|\n| Operating margin | 38.84% | 26.40% | +12.44 pp |\n| Segment Adjusted EBITDA margin | 62.95% | 50.65% | +12.30 pp |\n\n### Interpretation — Operating Leverage\n\nThe differential growth rates reveal strong positive operating leverage in the Connectivity segment:\n\n1. **Operating income grew ~2.4x faster than revenue** (120.49% vs. 49.85%). Each incremental dollar of revenue dropped to operating income at a substantially higher rate than the prior-year blended margin, indicating that a large portion of the segment's cost base is fixed or semi-fixed (satellite constellation infrastructure, ground stations, network operations) and is being spread over a rapidly expanding subscriber/revenue base.\n\n2. **Segment Adjusted EBITDA grew ~1.7x faster than revenue** (86.23% vs. 49.85%). This confirms the operating-leverage story on a cash-oriented basis, with EBITDA margin expanding ~12.3 percentage points year-over-year.\n\n3. **Operating income grew faster than Segment Adjusted EBITDA** (120.49% vs. 86.23%). Because Segment Adjusted EBITDA = Operating Income + (D&A + SBC + Restructuring + Impairment), this differential implies that the aggregate non-cash/non-recurring add-backs grew more slowly than operating income — and more slowly than revenue. This is consistent with (a) a maturing capital base where incremental D&A from new satellite launches is lagging revenue growth, and (b) share-based compensation scaling sub-linearly with the business. In other words, the GAAP profitability picture is improving even faster than the cash-EBITDA picture, reinforcing the operating-leverage conclusion.\n\n4. **Magnitude of margin expansion (~12 pp in both measures)** is unusually large for a segment already at scale ($7.6B → $11.4B revenue), suggesting Connectivity is passing an inflection point where fixed network costs are largely absorbed and incremental subscribers are highly accretive to profit.\n\n### Caveats\n\n- All figures reflect the retrospectively recast consolidated SpaceX entity (including xAI, merged February 2, 2026, and X Holdings, merged into xAI March 28, 2025) for all historical periods presented. The S-1 states that no period reflects standalone SpaceX operations exclusively; however, the Connectivity segment figures are presented on a segment basis and the recast consolidation primarily affects the consolidated/other segments rather than Connectivity's Starlink-driven economics.\n- Segment Adjusted EBITDA is a non-GAAP measure; its construction excludes D&A, SBC, restructuring, and impairment, all of which are economically real costs. The faster growth of GAAP operating income relative to this non-GAAP measure is itself a positive signal, but the EBITDA figure should not be treated as a proxy for free cash flow.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nThe Connectivity segment exhibited pronounced positive operating leverage in FY2025: ~50% revenue growth translated into ~120% operating income growth and ~86% Segment Adjusted EBITDA growth, with both margins expanding by roughly 12 percentage points. The fact that GAAP operating income outgrew Segment Adjusted EBITDA further indicates that non-cash charges (notably D&A and SBC) are scaling sub-linearly with revenue, reinforcing that the segment's fixed-cost infrastructure is being monetized with increasing efficiency as the Starlink subscriber base scales.\n\n{\n  \"sources\": [\n    {\n      \"url\": \"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\",\n      \"name\": \"SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Segment Reporting and MD&A sections\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
